{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"3.6.3"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"competition","sourceId":100890,"databundleVersionId":12488425},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":6066534,"datasetId":3471993,"databundleVersionId":6144877},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":12488729,"datasetId":9,"databundleVersionId":13066693}],"dockerImageVersionId":30069,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Introduction","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">For the past 15 years, Kaggle has been a meeting place for people from the Data and AI fields, creating a well-known environment for learning, publishing projects, and new challenges in these areas. Well, a meeting place... but <strong>how often have users actually cooperated</strong> over the last 15 years? [1]</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Today, we will dive into the world of cooperation when it comes to data and answer a simple and specific, but important question - is it worth Kaggling alone or with someone else? By \"Kaggling\" we mean any activity of registered users on this portal (in particular, participating in competitions, creating databases, creating notebooks, or participating in discussions), but our <strong>main focus is competitions</strong> (without \"InClass\" category). This is due to the fact that creating notebooks or publishing datasets by more than one user is extremely rare, so much so that we do not have registered metadata on this subject, unlike competitions in which teams often reach the top of the tables and at the same time they are the most famous activity on Kaggle.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The analysis can be complicated at times, and the statements related to the number of teams are a bit boring, so...let's call Kaggle users <strong>superheroes</strong> - after all, the things they do with data are often amazing. We divide data superheroes into 3 types based on superheroes commonly known in pop culture:</p>\n\n*  **Be like Superman** a loner type, a person who acts alone. Superman is the one who enjoys all the effects of his work, but need to deal with problems on his own. As a Superman, we mean people who **work on Kaggle alone** - they take part in competitions themselves, create a one-man team (or maybe even a one-man army)\n\n* **Be like Batman and Robin** a pair of superheroes who fight together for one common goal. Even though Batman surpasses Robin, who is his helper, they form a small team together and their cooperation is crucial to success. By Batman and Robin, we mean people who **work on Kaggle in team of 2**, taking part in competitions together\n\n* **Be like Avengers** a team of many people working together to achieve a common goal. They aren't the same at all, but maybe this differentiation is their strength? As avengers, we consider Kaggle users **working in larger teams than a pair** (minimum 3 people), taking part in competitions\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We can look for advantages and disadvantages of each option, but as data miners, we will look at the data and what information it carry. Are you ready for a journey through the world of data superheroes? Get in the superhero vehicle and fasten your seat belts!</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Setting in options not to display warning content, the appropriate way of displaying numbers and the width of charts\noptions(warn = -1)\noptions(scipen = 10000)\noptions(repr.plot.width = 20.0, repr.plot.height = 13.3)\n\n# Loading the necessary packages for data transformation and creating and displaying charts\nlibrary(tidyverse)\nlibrary(scales)\nlibrary(RColorBrewer)\nlibrary(ggthemes)\nlibrary(lubridate)\nlibrary(viridis)\nlibrary(ggrepel)\nlibrary(reshape)\nlibrary(gridExtra)\nlibrary(readr)\nlibrary(patchwork)\nannotate <- ggplot2::annotate\n\n# Creating your own unique background that will be the base - changing the size and colors of the appropriate texts and choosing the location of the legend [4]\ntheme_michau <- theme(legend.position = \"top\", legend.direction = \"horizontal\", axis.text = element_text(size = 20.4,  color = \"gray15\"), \nplot.caption = element_text(color = \"gray70\", face = \"bold\", size = 12), legend.text = element_text(size = 19.8,  color = \"gray15\"),\naxis.title = element_text(size = 21.9, face = \"bold\", color = \"gray15\"), legend.title = element_text(size = 19.8,  color = \"gray15\"), \naxis.line = element_line(size = 0.5), plot.title = element_text(size = 27.8,  color = \"gray15\"), plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 20.2,  color = \"gray15\"), \nstrip.text = element_text(size = 18.8, face = \"bold\", color = \"gray15\"))","metadata":{"_uuid":"051d70d956493feee0c6d64651c6a088724dca2a","_execution_state":"idle","_kg_hide-input":true,"_kg_hide-output":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:22:58.812921Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:22:58.815909Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:23:00.308833Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:23:00.307094Z"},"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">For this exploratory analysis, we'll use <strong>R along with additional packages</strong>. The technology may not be the newest and is becoming increasingly extinct, but like superheroes, we do not focus on fashion but on efficiency, and for data storytelling and visualization, it is still a great solution.\n    \n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The most important of them will be packages collected in the \"tidyverse\" package (dyplr, ggplot..), which allow for easy manipulation, preparation, analysis and visualization of data. In addition, loaded additional packages to create better charts such as RColorBrewer, ggthemes or ggrepel [2][3]. For the charts we will use a combination of two backgrounds - \"fivethirtyeight\" and our own with changes primarily to the size of fonts and elements on the chart (legends etc.). [4]</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">For technical people, the code will be continuously explained with comments in English - just click \"Show hidden code\" to see the full text with explanation.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Loading data from the \"meta-kaggle\" dataset. We select 4 tables containing a complete set of data and load them separately from csv files, without encoding\n\nTeamMemberships <- read.csv(\"/kaggle/input/meta-kaggle/TeamMemberships.csv\")\nTeams <- read.csv(\"/kaggle/input/meta-kaggle/Teams.csv\")\nSubmission <- read.csv(\"/kaggle/input/meta-kaggle/Submissions.csv\")\nCompetitions <- read.csv(\"/kaggle/input/meta-kaggle/Competitions.csv\")","metadata":{"_kg_hide-output":true,"_kg_hide-input":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:23:00.311088Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:23:00.339881Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:32:01.985835Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:32:01.98404Z"},"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">For the analysis, we use the great <strong>dataset prepared by Kaggle Team, containing a number of detailed information about user activities throughout 15 years of activity</strong> (competitions, discussions, notebooks and databases) stored in many tables. We are interested in <strong>4 tables</strong>: TeamMemberships, Teams, Submission and Competitions [5]. So let's check whether it is better to be Superman or Batman and Robin or maybe Avengers: who has a better chance of success on Kaggle, which heroes achieve greater successes and medals on average? Let's shift into a higher gear and get to the point.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculates the number of members in each team and stores it in 'People'.\n People <- TeamMemberships %>% \n  group_by(TeamId) %>% \n  summarise(Members = n()) \n\n # Joins the 'People' data with 'TeamMemberships' based on 'TeamId'.\n TeamMemberships <- TeamMemberships %>% \n  left_join(People, by = \"TeamId\") \n\n # Counts the frequency of teams based on their member count and categorizes them.\n Frequency <- TeamMemberships %>%  \n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>% \n  group_by(Members) %>% \n  summarise(Count = n()) %>% \n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\", \n           Members == 2  ~ \"2\", \n           Members > 2  ~ \"3+\")) \n\n # Extracts and scales the count of teams with 1 member.\n Count_1Member <- as.numeric(Frequency %>% \n  filter(Members2 == \"1\") %>% \n  mutate(Count = Count/10^6) %>% \n  select(Count)) \n\n # Extracts and scales the count of teams with 2 members.\n Count_2Member <- as.numeric(Frequency %>% \n  filter(Members2 == \"2\") %>% \n  mutate(Count = Count/10^6) %>% \n  select(Count)) \n\n # Extracts and scales the count of teams with 3 or more members.\n Count_3Member <- Frequency %>% \n  filter(!Members2 %in% c(\"1\", \"2\")) %>% \n  mutate(Count = Count/10^6) %>% \n  pull(Count) \n\n # Creates a bar plot to visualize team frequency by member count.\n # Sets custom fill colors and adds percentage labels to the bars.\n # Adds title, subtitle, axis labels, and a caption.\n # Applies custom themes for styling and hides the legend.\n ggplot(Frequency, aes(Members2, Count/10^6, fill = Members2))+ \n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.78, alpha = 0.95)+ \n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+ \n  annotate(\"text\", x = 1, y = Count_1Member/2, label = paste0(100*round(Count_1Member/(sum(Frequency$Count)/10^6), 3), \"%\"), size = 8.7, col = \"gray95\")+ \n  annotate(\"text\", x = 2, y = 3.5*Count_2Member, label = paste0(100*round(Count_2Member/(sum(Frequency$Count)/10^6), 3), \"%\"), size = 8.7, col = \"gray15\")+ \n  annotate(\"text\", x = 3, y = 4*sum(Count_3Member), label = paste0(100*round(sum(Count_3Member)/(sum(Frequency$Count)/10^6), 3), \"%\"), size = 8.7, col = \"gray15\")+ \n  labs(title = \"Frequency of analyzed groups\", \n    subtitle = \"Number of team = team in single competitons, no submission required\", \n    x = \"Number of Kagglers in the team\", y = \"Number of teams (in milions)\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+ \n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+ \n  theme_michau+ \n  theme(legend.position = \"none\")","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:32:01.988227Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:32:01.989512Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:34:41.126916Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:34:41.125062Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We start our adventure with superheroes by counting them. The unit we use is a team per competition, which means that we can count teams multiple times if they took part in more than one competition (e.g. if someone took part solo in 10 competitions, we will count 10 points towards the total of Supermen). You don't have to have Superman's eyesight to see the <strong>overwhelming advantage of single-person teams</strong> over pairs and teams of 3+. There are almost 8 million participants as Supermen, while Batman with Robin and the Avengers had about 75,000 each. Avengers consist of 3 to 40 people, but most often it is a number between 3 and 5, because these are often the rules of competitions. It is worth noting that these are entries to competitions that do not require any submission. However, it will turn out that the result of Supermen still exceeds 90% even if we only take into account teams with at least one entry.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>The participation of Supermen is quite overwhelming</strong>, so it is worth thinking a little longer - <strong>why is it so huge?</strong> We can make some assumptions, many people start the adventure alone and want to learn as much as possible by leading the project from start to finish. Many people would like to take part in a team but they did not manage to gather one, some took part in the competition but due to lack of time and motivation they abandoned it and did not look for a team, having large language models we may prefer consultations with a virtual assistant instead of another human being... we could go on and on creating countless scenarios. However, instead of blindly inventing, <strong>let's see in the paper what makes people facing similar challenges so often prefer to work alone</strong>.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">There are quite a lot of articles on the broad topic of cooperation preferences and individual work, but let's limit ourselves to a few. Since the 90s, the term \"Social Loafing\" has been used, proving that working in a group translates into less effort put into the project compared to individual work [6]. Kagglers may prefer to work alone, because taking part in the competition requires a lot of intellectual effort, which they are much better able to do when working alone.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Working in a group also translates into a much larger number of all kinds of distractions, things that divert attention from hard work. This phenomenon has been studied in software development, so in a very similar field to Kaggle competitions, after all, both here and there you work with programming code [7]. Also last year, a study was released confirming that all kinds of breaks have a clear negative impact on software development [8], and such breaks are much more frequent when working in groups.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">It is also worth not forgetting about behavioral issues - we can find information in the research articles about the self-determination theory, according to which a person needs a certain kind of autonomy and competition. The choice of individual participation in the competition can be driven by such needs that, on the one hand, allow for full control of one's own actions and decisions (which is impossible in the case of cooperation in a group) and also allows for satisfying the need for competence, wanting to prove one's independent skills [9].</p>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The question now arises - <strong>is Kaggle unique in this proportion?</strong>, or are similar competitions in which there is, in principle, freedom in choosing the size of the team also characterized by a large dominance of single-person teams? Unfortunately, it is hard to find a good example of a similar platform with similar rules that registers its data. However, we can compare our data to another very popular activity related to Data Science / AI in which there is complete freedom as to independence and work in a group - <strong>writing research articles</strong>.</p>\n    \n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We managed to find a collection that publishes metadata about articles only in the field of AI. It contains a sample of exactly 10,000 such articles, linked from 1993 to 2023 [10]. All of them were published on one of the most popular websites on this subject, i.e. arxiv, a free distribution service and an open-access archive for nearly 2.4 million scholarly articles in many fields including computer science [11].</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Despite the visible differences between both activities (but also common elements), let's check if the distribution of groups is similar.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Joins 'Submission' with 'People' data frames based on 'TeamId'.\nSubmission <- Submission %>%\n  left_join(People, by = \"TeamId\")\n\n# Selects unique submissions and categorizes them by the number of team members.\n# Then, it counts occurrences and calculates percentages for each category.\nDistributionTotal <- Submission %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = T) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  group_by(Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count))\n\n# Reads a CSV file containing AI research paper data.\nArticlesAI <- read.csv('/kaggle/input/arxivorg-ai-research-papers-dataset/arxiv_ai.csv')\n\n# Defines a function to count authors from a formatted string.\ncount_authors <- function(author_string) {\n  if (author_string == \"[]\") {\n    return(0)\n  } else {\n    # Cleans the author string and splits it into individual authors.\n    cleaned_string <- str_replace_all(author_string, \"\\\\[arxiv\\\\.Result\\\\.Author\\\\('\", \"\")\n    cleaned_string <- str_replace_all(cleaned_string, \"'\\\\)\\\\]\", \"\")\n    \n    authors_list <- str_split(cleaned_string, \"'\\\\), arxiv\\\\.Result\\\\.Author\\\\('\")[[1]]\n    \n    return(length(authors_list))\n  }\n}\n\n# Applies the author counting function to each row and categorizes counts.\nArticlesAI$Authors_count <- sapply(ArticlesAI$authors, count_authors)\nArticlesAI$Authors_count2 <- ifelse(ArticlesAI$Authors_count > 2, \"3+\", as.character(ArticlesAI$Authors_count))\n\n# Groups the data by author count categories.\n# It then calculates the count and percentage for each group.\nArticlesAI <- ArticlesAI %>%\n  group_by(Authors_count2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n()) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:34:41.129112Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:34:41.130373Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:34:54.914319Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:34:54.912669Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Creates a bar chart for Kaggle competition participation, setting aesthetics, bar properties, and labels.\n# It uses custom colors and FiveThirtyEight theme with additional custom theme adjustments.\nKaggle <- ggplot(DistributionTotal, aes(x = Members2, y = percentage, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(percentage, accuracy = 1)), vjust = -0.5, color = \"gray15\", size = 7.5)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, limits = c(0, 1), breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.2))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  labs(title = \"Kaggle Competitions: group participation\",\n       subtitle = \"Sample = all competition, around 1.2 mln entrances in 2010-2025\",\n       x = \"Team size\", y = \"Share of team\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.position = \"none\")\n\n# Creates a similar bar chart for AI paper author participation using the same visual styling.\nArticles <- ggplot(ArticlesAI, aes(x = Authors_count2, y = percentage, fill = Authors_count2))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(percentage, accuracy = 1)), vjust = -0.5, color = \"gray15\", size = 7.5)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, limits = c(0, 1), breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.2))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  labs(title = \"AI Papers: group participation\",\n       subtitle = \"Sample = 10,000 articles in 1993-2023\",\n       x = \"Team size\", y = \"Share of team\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.position = \"none\")\n\n# Combines the two generated plots side-by-side for comparison and display\nCombinedPlot <- (Kaggle | Articles)\nprint(CombinedPlot)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:34:54.916712Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:34:54.918011Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:34:55.704612Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:34:55.702294Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">From the papers database, we extract the number of authors and reduce them to the same categories as our supermen: 1, 2 and 3+ people in a team. On Kaggle, if we take only teams that published at least 1 solution to the competition, we see that 93% are supermen (less than when counting situations with no submissions, but still an overwhelming majority), while pairs and larger teams constitute 4% and 3% respectively. The sample from 15 years and all competitions covered slightly over 1.2 million teams.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">In AI papers, we have a smaller sample and a wider time range, but the differences are clearly visible: Supermen published only every fifth scientific article (21%). Batman and Robin contributed about 2,800 articles out of 10,000, while over half, or as much as 51%, are Avengers.<strong>So the difference is huge, when publishing articles people form teams much more often than when participating in competitions on Kaggle (despite similar topics around AI)</strong>. However, it is worth taking into account the different data period and sample size. Let's also remember that the activity of writing scientific articles has a different character: it is not limited by time, number of submissions or strict form. However, we can be sure that it is not the <strong>topic of AI itself that makes people work alone - writing articles brings people together to cooperate, so it seems that the form of competition itself has a much greater impact</strong> on the dominance of one-man army.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Analysis in time","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Now that we know that Supermen dominates, let's look at these groups over time. <strong>Has the dominance of Supermen really been so significant since forever?</strong> And can we indicate that this will continue to be the case in the near future? Let's start with the annual overshoot for the last 15 years (or really 16, because even though Kaggle is 15 years old, its calendar covers parts of 2010 and 2025).</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Extracts the year from 'SubmissionDate' and stores it in a new 'Year' column.\nSubmission$Year <- year(as.Date(Submission$SubmissionDate, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))\n\n# Processes submission data to categorize teams by member count and year.\n# Groups data by year and team size, then counts occurrences, and removes NA values.\nDistribution <- Submission %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F)\n\n# Filters for 2012 data to calculate the percentage of non-solo teams.\n# Summarizes counts, computes the ratio, formats it as a percentage string.\nRecord_Year <- Distribution %>%\n  filter(Year == 2012) %>%\n  summarise(two_plus = sum(count[Members2 != 1]), all = sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(divide = two_plus / all, percent = paste0(round(divide * 100), \"%\")) %>%\n  pull(percent)\n\n# Formats the calculated percentage for display on the plot.\nRecord_Year <- paste0(\"Non-solo\\nteams:\\n\", Record_Year)\n\n# Creates a stacked bar chart showing team distribution by year and member count.\n# Sets aesthetic mappings, bar properties, and axis labels.\n# Adds custom colors and legend title.\n# Annotates the plot with the 'Record_Year' text and an arrow pointing to it.\n# Defines the plot title, subtitle, axis labels, and caption.\n# Applies custom themes for styling.\nggplot(Distribution, aes(x = Year, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2010, 2025, 1))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  annotate(\"text\", x = 2012, y = 0.3, label = Record_Year, size = 4.5, col = \"gray95\")+\n  annotate(geom = \"curve\", xend = 2012, y = 0.25, x = 2012, yend = 0.12, curvature = 0, \n           arrow = arrow(length = unit(4.5, \"mm\")), colour = \"gray85\", size = 0.6)+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by year\",\n       subtitle = \"in all competitions \\nonly teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Year\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:34:55.707269Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:34:55.708673Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:35:12.3014Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:35:12.298543Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">As you can see, the <strong>differences between years are not large, and each time the people taking part in the competition themselves has over 90%</strong> of all teams each year. The record year in terms of teams with at least 2 users was 2012, when such teams constituted about 9% of the entire population. The fluctuations are so small that it is difficult to find trends in relation to non-solo teams. However, it can be noticed that compared to the first years of Kaggle's operation, the Avengers are gaining in importance at the expense of Batman and Robin. In the past, the advantage of pairs was significant among 2+ teams (2010-2015), but in recent years there has been a slight surplus of 3+ teams over pairs (2023-2024). Remember that 2025 is still here and the mid-year sample should be treated with caution.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We already know the historical values and know about the low variability, but the perspective of looking into the future is so interesting that we will try to <strong>make a forecast of what the distribution of superheroes may look like in the next five years</strong>.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We will use simple modeling for this - our Y is the percentage share of a specific group at a specific moment in time (values for the full year 2026, 2027..) and the explanatory feature (X) is the year of observation. So we are creating 3 models: for Supermen, Batman & Robin's, and for Avengers separately.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We decide to use the <strong>polynominal regression</strong> method [12] presented by the formula.</p>\n\n$$y=\\beta _{0}+\\beta _{1}Year+\\beta _{2}Year^{2}+\\varepsilon \\, $$\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">By using this method we achieve a compromise between the simplicity of the model (we only have one feature and few observations, so we choose something not too advanced so as not to overfit the model but to detect a general relationship) and its predictive abilities (the trends according to the graph above seem to be non-linear, so the method of raising the explanatory feature to a power will help to solve this problem).</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Process submission data, creating a 'Members2' category based on team size.\n# Group data by year and team size, then calculate percentage of each group.\nTime <- Submission %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = T) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2 ~ \"3+\"\n                              )) %>%\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop_last') %>%\n  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count)) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F)\n\n# Create a tibble for future years, from the current max year up to 2030.\nFutureYears <- tibble(Year = seq(max(Time$Year) + 1, 2030, 1))\n\n# Initialize an empty data frame to store future predictions.\nPredictions <- data.frame()\n\n# Loop through each 'Members2' group to build a regression model.\n# Predict future percentages for each group and ensure values are within 0-1.\n# Combine predictions with previous results.\nfor (group in unique(Time$Members2)) {\n  group_data <- Time %>% filter(Members2 == group)\n  model <- lm(percentage ~ Year + I(Year^2), data = group_data)\n  predicted_percentage <- predict(model, newdata = FutureYears)\n\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage < 0] <- 0\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage > 1] <- 1\n\n  Predictions <- bind_rows(Predictions, tibble(Year = FutureYears$Year, Members2 = group, percentage = predicted_percentage, type = \"Predicted\"))\n}\n\n# Add a 'type' column to the original data, labeling it as \"Real data\".\nTime <- Time %>%\n  mutate(type = \"Real data\")\n\n# Combine real data and predictions for plotting.\nTimePrediction <- bind_rows(Time, Predictions) %>%\n  arrange(Members2, Year)\n\n# Generate a line plot showing historical and predicted group percentages.\n# Customize plot aesthetics including colors, labels, and legends.\nggplot(TimePrediction , aes(x = Year, y = percentage, fill = Members2, color = Members2))+\n  geom_line(aes(alpha = type), size = 1.4, type = \"solid\", show.legend = T)+\n  geom_point(data = filter(TimePrediction, type == \"Real data\"), size = 6, alpha = 0.95, shape = 21)+\n  scale_y_continuous(trans = \"log10\", labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1), limits = c(0.01, 1))+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(TimePrediction$Year), 2030, 1))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_alpha_manual(values = c(\"Real data\" = 1, \"Predicted\" = 0.4), name = \"Observation\")+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 1), alpha = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 2, reverse = T), colour = \"none\")+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by year + predictions up to 2030\", subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\\nprediction method: polynominal regression\",\n       x = \"Year\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions (log scale)\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5, legend.box = \"horizontal\", legend.box.spacing = unit(1.5, \"cm\"), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 18.2))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:35:12.305121Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:35:12.307748Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:35:15.267239Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:35:15.264674Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The charts use a log scale because the lines for Batman & Robin and the Avengers overlap significantly, reducing readability. The results of all three models are quite clear: the <strong>models predict a small increase in the share of Supermen</strong> (it's hard to see a huge increase, because the values are sometimes close to 100%) <strong>and a decrease among the other groups</strong>. At the moment, groups of two and 3+ people are more or less at the same level, but a faster decrease is predicted among pairs. So in a few years, will 2 and 3+ groups be even more \"exotic\" than they are today? Models are just predictions, so we have to wait until empirical data appears.</p>","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Competition participation","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We already know how the participation in the group was shaped over time. Now let's get into the issue of participation in competitions related to the names of the most popular competitions in which all three groups took part, the number of entries to the competitions and the medals won (in general and over the years).</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Renames the first column of 'Teams' to 'TeamId' and 'Competitions' to 'CompetitionId' for consistency.\nnames(Teams)[1] <- \"TeamId\"\nnames(Competitions)[1] <- \"CompetitionId\"\n\n# Joins 'Teams' with 'Submission' and then with 'Competitions' dataframes.\nTeams <- Teams %>%\n  left_join(Submission, by = \"TeamId\")\n\nTeams <- Teams %>%\n  left_join(Competitions, by = \"CompetitionId\")\n\n# Filters out \"InClass\" competitions and duplicate TeamIds, then processes team members data.\n# It then categorizes teams by member count (1, 2, or 3+) and counts teams per competition title.\n# Finally, it filters for solo teams with over 4000 entries and creates a bar plot.\nSuperman <- Teams %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle != \"InClass\") %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == F) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members) == F) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  group_by(Title, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(Members2 == \"1\" & count > 4000) %>%\nggplot(., aes(x = reorder(Title, +count), y = count))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.65, fill = \"#003f5c\", alpha = 0.95)+\n  coord_flip()+\n  labs(title = \"Number of Kagglers: 1\",\n       subtitle = \"> 4,000 teams with at least 1 submission\",\n       y = \"Number of teams\", x = \"Competition title\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 9.5), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9.8), axis.title.x = element_text(size = 10.8),\n        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 21.9, face = \"bold\", color = \"gray15\"),\n        plot.title = element_text(size = 14.8), plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 11.8))\n\n# Filters out \"InClass\" competitions and duplicate TeamIds, then categorizes teams by member count.\n# It then counts teams per competition title for teams with 2 members and over 250 entries, generating a bar plot.\nBatmanRobin <- Teams %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle != \"InClass\") %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == F) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Title, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(Members2 == \"2\" & count > 250) %>%\nggplot(., aes(x = reorder(Title, +count), y = count))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.65, fill = \"#ef5675\", alpha = 0.95)+\n  coord_flip()+\n  labs(title = \"Number of Kagglers: 2\",\n       subtitle = \"> 250 teams with at least 1 submission\",\n       y = \"Number of teams\", x = \"\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 9.5), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9.8), axis.title = element_text(size = 10.8),\n        plot.title = element_text(size = 14.8), plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 11.8))\n\n# Filters out \"InClass\" competitions and duplicate TeamIds, then categorizes teams by member count.\n# It then counts teams per competition title for teams with 3+ members and over 250 entries, generating a bar plot.\nAvengers <- Teams %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle != \"InClass\") %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == F) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Title, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(Members2 == \"3+\" & count > 250) %>%\nggplot(., aes(x = reorder(Title, +count), y = count))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.65, fill = \"#ffa600\", alpha = 0.95)+\n  coord_flip()+\n  labs(title = \"Number of Kagglers: 3+\",\n       subtitle = \"> 250 teams with at least 1 submission\",\n       y = \"Number of teams\", x = \"\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 9.5), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9.8), axis.title = element_text(size = 10.8),\n        plot.title = element_text(size = 14.8), plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 11.8))\n\n# Filters data, categorizes teams by member count, and calculates total teams per competition.\n# It then summarizes team counts by category and competition, filtering for competitions with over 4500 teams.\n# Finally, it creates a stacked bar chart showing team distribution by member count.\nAll <- Teams %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle != \"InClass\") %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == FALSE) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == FALSE) %>%\n  group_by(Title) %>%\n  mutate(count2 = n()) %>%\n  ungroup() %>%\n  group_by(Title, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(),\n            count2 = first(count2),\n            .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  filter(count2 > 4500) %>%\nggplot(., aes(x = reorder(Title, +count), y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 0.65, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"), reverse = T)+\n  coord_flip()+\n  labs(title = \"Competitions with the largest number of teams\",\n       subtitle = \"> 4,500 teams, diveded into gruops\\nonly not InClass competitions and teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Competition title\", y = \"Number of teams\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12.8), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12.8))\n\n# Arranges the generated plots: 'All' plot on top, with 'Superman', 'BatmanRobin', and 'Avengers' side-by-side below.\nCombinedPlot <- All / (Superman | BatmanRobin | Avengers)\nprint(CombinedPlot)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:35:15.270963Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:35:15.273262Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:37:21.321896Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:37:21.319711Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">First, let's take a look at the most popular official competitions (excluding \"inClass\" competitions). We will do this in four configurations: all teams at once and each group separately. <strong>Looking at all of them, the clear leader is \"Santander Consumer Transaction Prediction\"</strong>. This is the only competition in which almost 9,000 teams took part, it took place in 2019 and concerned \"identify which customers will make a specific transaction in the future irrespective of the amount of money transacted\" [13]. We have a total of 10 competitions in which the number of teams with at least 1 successful submission was over 4,500. Knowing the information from the previous charts, it is not surprising to us that in each of these competitions supermen dominated. The competition from the top in which the percentage was the smallest is \"M5 - Forecasting - Accuracy\" from 2020, in which participants had to predict daily sales at Walmart based on historical sales data [14].</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\"><strong>Among the Supermen, the most popular competition is also undoubtedly Santander Consumer Transaction Prediction</strong>. It was a relatively simple competition with tabular data and a high prize pool, which allowed it to attract over 8,000 one-person teams and is a big leader. So far, 13 competitions have been held, in which over 4,000 Supermen took part. The ranking list is very similar to the general list (which is not surprising, as the general list is made up of over 90% of the Supermen).</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Since we know where the Supermen were most often, we track down the Batmans and Robins. It turns out that where the Supermen were, the <strong>competitions organized by Santander were most often attended by two-person teams</strong>. Second place is also the same as in the case of the Supermen, the \"Home Credit Default Risk\" competition. The differences in the ranking compared to the Supermen are already visible in the subsequent positions. The \"Porto Seguro's Safe Driver Prediction\" competition was relatively unpopular among pairs. So far, only 12 competitions have gathered more than 250 Batman & Robin taking part in a joint event (and only 4 of them more than 300).</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">At the end of a short adventure with the most popular competitions, we check where the Avengers traveled most often, groups of at least 3 data superheroes. We see a change in the leadership position in relation to the previous groups - <strong>the largest number of groups of several or a dozen people took part in the \"Home Credit Default Risk\"</strong> competition, predicting whether a loan will be repaid (binary classification problem) [15]. The \"Woman in Data Science\" community competitions have also become popular among groups - among the 7 most popular Avengers competitions, as many as 3 are editions of this challenge from 2021-2023 [16]. So far, over 250 groups of at least 3 people have taken part in 13 competitions - similarly to the case of pairs.</p>\n\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Now let's take a closer look at the distribution of submissions between superhero groups.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Creates a data frame from the frequency of TeamId in the Teams data.\n# Renames columns and converts TeamId to numeric.\nTableSubmission <- as.data.frame(table(Teams$TeamId))\nnames(TableSubmission) <- c(\"TeamId\", \"Submi\")\nTableSubmission$TeamId <- as.numeric(as.character(TableSubmission$TeamId))\n\n# Joins with Teams data, removes duplicate teams, and filters out \"InClass\" segments.\n# Categorizes team members into 1, 2, or 3+ groups and removes NAs.\nTableSubmission <- TableSubmission %>%\n  left_join(Teams, by = \"TeamId\") %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = T) %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle != \"InClass\") %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2 ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F)\n\n# Groups data by Members2, calculates average submissions, and renames columns.\nMeanSubmission <- TableSubmission %>%\n  group_by(Members2) %>%\n  summarise(Avg_Submi = round(mean(Submi, na.rm = T), 0)) %>%\n  ungroup() %>%\n  dplyr::rename(` Number of Kagglers ` = Members2, ` Avg. submissions ` = Avg_Submi)\n\n# Creates a table graphic of MeanSubmission with custom themes for styling.\nMeanSubmission <- tableGrob(MeanSubmission, rows = NULL,\n                            theme = ttheme_default(\n                              core = list(bg_params = list(fill = c(\"gray99\", \"gray89\")),\n                                          fg_params = list(col = \"gray15\", fontsize = 20.5)),\n                              colhead = list(fg_params = list(col = \"gray15\", fontsize = 22, fontface = \"bold\")),\n                              rowhead = list(fg_params = list(col = \"gray15\", fontsize = 20.5))\n                            ))\n\n# Generates a box plot using TableSubmission.\n# Sets custom colors, adds the MeanSubmission table as an annotation, and applies labels.\n# Uses specific themes and removes the legend.\nggplot(TableSubmission, aes(Members2, Submi, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_boxplot(outlier.size = 1.8, outlier.shape = 20, outlier.alpha = 0.35,\n               lwd = 0.8, fatten = 1.4, colour = \"gray15\", alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(trans = \"log10\", labels = scales::comma)+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  annotation_custom(grob = MeanSubmission, xmin = 2.4, xmax = Inf, ymin = 4, ymax = Inf)+\n  labs(title = \"Number of submissions entered in competitions by analyzed groups\", subtitle = \"only not InClass competitions and teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Number of submissions (logarithmic scale)\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.position = \"none\")","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:37:21.32421Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:37:21.325532Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:28.086907Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:28.084954Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The competition entries themselves are not individual, you can almost always publish more than one model in one competition. These issues are regulated in the competition rules, most often through daily submission limits. The distribution of the number of submissions is visualized using boxplots (separate for each group) and on the vertical axis we use a logarithmic scale to improve readability and better show differences.</p>\n    \n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">At first glance, there is an obvious relationship - <strong>the larger the team, the greater the number of submissions</strong>. Among Supermen, the median number of entries for the competition is single-digit, and the average is 12. Situations in which a single-person team submits several hundred submissions are rare. For pairs, the average number of models is more than twice as many as in the previous group (26), and for larger groups it is 44. Of course, the number of submissions can naturally be higher if we have more people in the team, because this produces more ideas for a new model/solution. However, it is worth noting that <strong>when we divide the number of submissions by the number of people in the team, it is still slightly higher in large teams</strong>. Could it be that group work motivates members to make further attempts? Or maybe participation in groups is often taken much more seriously than individual attempts?</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Let's get to the submissions that turned out to be the most effective and were awarded medals.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Selects relevant columns and keeps only unique team entries.\nTeams %>%\n  select(TeamId, Medal, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  # Categorizes 'Medal' into \"Gold\", \"Silver\", \"Bronze\", or \"None\", and 'Members' into \"1\", \"2\", or \"3+\".\n  mutate(Medal2 = case_when(Medal < 2 ~ \"Gold\",\n                            Medal == 2  ~ \"Silver\",\n                            Medal > 2  ~ \"Bronze\",\n                            is.na(Medal) == T ~ \"None\"\n  )) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  # Filters out entries where 'Members2' is missing and counts occurrences.\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Medal2, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), , .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  # Generates a bar plot showing the distribution of medals and team sizes, customizing aesthetics, labels, and themes.\nggplot(., aes(x = Medal2, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_x_discrete(limit = c(\"Gold\", \"Silver\", \"Bronze\", \"None\"))+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by medals\",\n       subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\", x = \"Medal\",\n       fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:28.089162Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:28.090483Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:33.281877Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:33.280026Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We check how the medals won are distributed depending on the groups, creating 4 stacked bars (for gold, silver, bronze and no medals). The relationship is very visible - <strong>the higher the medal rank, the greater the share of teams consisting of at least 2 people, and the lower the medal rank, the greater the share of single-person teams</strong>. 25% of gold medals are won by teams consisting of at least 3 people, while their number among all teams is only about 1% (20 times more effective than Supermen). A similar sentence is true for pairs, which are slightly less effective in winning medals than teams, but do much better than individuals. <strong>Batman & Robin and the Avengers, despite being a group of only a few percentage points, win almost 40% of gold medals and almost 30% of all medals</strong>. So do you want to increase your chances of winning a medal? Work in a group, the data here is absolutely clear.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">The question is whether it has always been like this since the beginning of the competitions? And whether in the future we will also have a relatively huge success of groups over individuals? Let's see...</p>","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filters for teams with less than two medals, selects relevant columns, and keeps only unique team entries.\nTeams %>%\n  filter(Medal < 2) %>%\n  select(TeamId, Medal, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  # Categorizes teams by the number of members, removes missing member categories.\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                               Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                               Members > 2 ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  # Joins with submission data, extracts the year, and filters out missing years.\n  left_join(select(Submission, TeamId, SubmissionDate), by = \"TeamId\") %>%\n  mutate(Year = year(as.Date(SubmissionDate, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Year) == F) %>%\n  # Groups data by year and member categories, then counts occurrences.\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  # Creates and customizes a filled bar chart to visualize the share of gold medals by group over the years.\nggplot(., aes(x = Year, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2010, 2025, 1))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  labs(\n    title = \"Share of gold medals by group throught years\",\n    subtitle = \"in all competitions \\nonly teams with at least one submission\",\n    x = \"Year\",\n    fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\",\n    y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\",\n    caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\") +\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:33.28423Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:33.285542Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:35.816893Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:35.815064Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Let's focus on the gold medals only for now - they are the goals of the competition and often come with valuable prizes. We create a bar chart representing the share of gold medals in the groups, with a separate bar showing the values for each year, starting from 2010.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">It turns out that the differences between years are quite large, especially when we compare the participation of groups after years were characterized by low variability. <strong>Winnings by pairs and teams started from a fairly low level in 2010 and then systematically increased (with smaller fluctuations) until 2018, where they reached their peak</strong>. 2018 was the peak, it is the only period in which more than half of the winners were Avengers and Batman & Robin were less than 25%. Since then, we have seen a decline and stabilization at a more or less equal level in the last 6 years.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We know what it was like based on empirical data. And what about based on forecasts?</p>","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filters teams with gold medals and selects relevant columns.\n# Keeps only distinct teams, then categorizes 'Members' into three groups.\nGoldMedals <- Teams %>%\n  filter(Medal < 2) %>%\n  select(TeamId, Medal, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2 ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  # Removes rows with missing 'Members2' values.\n  # Joins with 'Submission' data to add 'SubmissionDate' and extracts 'Year'.\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  left_join(select(Submission, TeamId, SubmissionDate), by = \"TeamId\") %>%\n  mutate(Year = year(as.Date(SubmissionDate, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))) %>%\n  # Filters out rows with missing 'Year', then groups data by year and member count.\n  # Summarizes the count of teams and calculates the percentage for each group.\n  filter(is.na(Year) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  group_by(Year) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(type = \"Real data\")\n\n# Creates a tibble of future years for predictions.\nfuture_years_df <- tibble(Year = seq(max(GoldMedals$Year) + 1, 2030, 1))\nGoldPredictions <- data.frame()\n\n# Loops through unique member groups to build and apply a linear model.\n# Predicts future percentages and constrains them between 0 and 1.\nfor (group in unique(GoldMedals$Members2)) {\n  group_data <- GoldMedals %>% filter(Members2 == group & type == \"Real data\")\n  model <- lm(percentage ~ Year + I(Year^2), data = group_data)\n  predicted_percentage <- predict(model, newdata = future_years_df)\n\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage < 0] <- 0\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage > 1] <- 1\n\n  # Combines predicted data with existing predictions.\n  GoldPredictions <- bind_rows(GoldPredictions, tibble(Year = future_years_df$Year, Members2 = group, percentage = predicted_percentage, type = \"Predicted\"))\n}\n\n# Combines real and predicted data, then sorts it.\nGoldFull <- bind_rows(GoldMedals, GoldPredictions) %>%\n  arrange(Members2, Year)\n\n# Creates a line plot showing the share of gold medals over time.\n# Adds points for real data and customizes scales and labels.\nggplot(GoldFull, aes(x = Year, y = percentage, fill = Members2, color = Members2))+\n  geom_line(aes(group = interaction(Members2, type), alpha = type), size = 1.6, linetype = \"solid\", show.legend = T)+\n  geom_point(data = filter(GoldFull, type == \"Real data\"), shape = 21, size = 6, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1), limits = c(0, 1))+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(GoldFull$Year), 2030, 1))+\n  # Defines manual colors and alpha levels for the plot elements.\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_alpha_manual(values = c(\"Real data\" = 1, \"Predicted\" = 0.4), name = \"Observation\")+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 1), alpha = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 2, reverse = T), color = \"none\")+\n  labs(title = \"Share of gold medals by group throught years + predcitions up to 2030\",\n       subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\\nprediction method: polynomial regression\",\n       x = \"Year\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5, legend.box = \"horizontal\", legend.box.spacing = unit(1.5, \"cm\"), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 17.8))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:35.819189Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:35.820457Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:40.193412Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:40.191015Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Similarly to point 2, we use polynomial regression for the same reasons as mentioned in the previous chapter and make predictions for 5 years ahead. According to the model, in the coming years the share of <strong>Superman among gold medalists should grow significantly each year</strong>, so that in 2030 it will reach a value above 75% and approach the record, which belongs to the first year on Kaggle. <strong>A slow decrease is predicted among Batmans and Robins, and a rapid decrease among Avengers</strong>, and within a few years the group will give place to pairs. It is worth approaching this forecast with great caution due to the simplicity of the model and relatively short history.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Gold medals are a fairly narrow group, though the most prestigious but also the smallest, resulting in a smaller data sample. So let's take a closer look at the populations - the groups that won the medal (regardless of color, equating gold, silver and bronze medalists).</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Cleans data by removing missing medal values, selecting relevant columns, and ensuring unique team entries.\nTeams %>%\n  filter(is.na(Medal) == F) %>%\n  select(TeamId, Medal, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%\n  # Categorizes teams by member count (1, 2, or 3+) and removes entries with missing member categories.\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2 ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  # Joins with submission data to extract and filter by year, then groups by year and member category to count occurrences.\n  left_join(select(Submission, TeamId, SubmissionDate), by = \"TeamId\") %>%\n  mutate(Year = year(as.Date(SubmissionDate, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Year) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  # Creates and customizes a stacked bar chart to visualize the share of all medals by group over the years.\nggplot(., aes(x = Year, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2010, 2025, 1))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  labs(title = \"Share of all medals by group throught years\", subtitle = \"in all competitions \\nonly teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Year\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\") +\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:40.197187Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:40.199115Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:44.824322Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:44.822508Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">As in the case of gold medals, the record year for Supermen was the first in the measurements 2010, after which there is an increase in the share of groups of 2+ people. This increase, however, is not as dynamic as in the case of gold models (much flatter), the biggest difference occurred between 2017 and 2018. <strong>Over the last 7 years, we have seen stabilization of all 3 groups at levels more or less: 55% of medals for Supermen, 15% of medals for Batman and Robin, and 30% of medals for Avengers</strong>.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">And what does the future hold in terms of the overall distribution of medals in groups?</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Processes team data to categorize members, extracts submission years, and calculates yearly participation percentages.\nAllMedals <- Teams %>%\n  filter(is.na(Medal) == F) %>%\n  select(TeamId, Medal, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2 ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2 ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  left_join(select(Submission, TeamId, SubmissionDate), by = \"TeamId\") %>%\n  mutate(Year = year(as.Date(SubmissionDate, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Year) == F) %>%\n  group_by(Year, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  group_by(Year) %>%\n  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(type = \"Real data\")\n\n# Creates a tibble of future years and initializes an empty data frame for predictions.\nfuture_years_df <- tibble(Year = seq(max(AllMedals$Year) + 1, 2030, 1))\nMedalsPrediction <- data.frame()\n\n# Iterates through each member group, builds a polynomial regression model, predicts future percentages, and appends to the prediction data frame.\nfor (group in unique(AllMedals$Members2)) {\n  group_data <- AllMedals %>% filter(Members2 == group & type == \"Real data\")\n  model <- lm(percentage ~ Year + I(Year^2), data = group_data)\n  predicted_percentage <- predict(model, newdata = future_years_df)\n\n  # Clamps predicted percentages between 0 and 1.\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage < 0] <- 0\n  predicted_percentage[predicted_percentage > 1] <- 1\n\n  MedalsPrediction <- bind_rows(MedalsPrediction, tibble(Year = future_years_df$Year, Members2 = group, percentage = predicted_percentage, type = \"Predicted\"))\n}\n\n# Combines real and predicted medal data, then visualizes the share of medals by group over years with predictions using lines and points.\nMedalsFull <- bind_rows(AllMedals, MedalsPrediction) %>%\n  arrange(Members2, Year)\n\nggplot(MedalsFull, aes(x = Year, y = percentage, fill = Members2, color = Members2))+\n  geom_line(aes(group = interaction(Members2, type), alpha = type), size = 1.6, linetype = \"solid\", show.legend = T)+\n  geom_point(data = filter(MedalsFull, type == \"Real data\"), shape = 21, size = 6, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1), limits = c(0, 1))+\n  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(MedalsFull$Year), 2030, 1))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  scale_alpha_manual(values = c(\"Real data\" = 1, \"Predicted\" = 0.4), name = \"Observation\")+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 1), alpha = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\", order = 2, reverse = T), color = \"none\")+\n  labs(title = \"Share of medals by group throught years + predcitions up to 2030\",\n       subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\\nprediction method: polynomial regression\",\n       x = \"Year\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5, legend.box = \"horizontal\", legend.box.spacing = unit(1.5, \"cm\"), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 18.2))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:44.82687Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:44.828207Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:50.904918Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:50.903027Z"},"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">This time, the forecasts suggest quite calm and slow changes in the ratio of forecasts concerning only gold medals. <strong>A very slow increase in the share of Supermen is forecasted</strong> (by about 1 percentage point per year), so a return to the level above 70% should not happen soon. <strong>A similar increase is forecasted for Avengers. A slow decline is probable for Batman & Robin by about 1.5-2 percentage points per year</strong>, according to the model.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">We know more about the superhero submissions and medals, but the competitions differ in the type of challenges, the methods of assessments, and the number and quality of prizes, which we'll look at in Chapter 4.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Competition metadata","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">First, let's look at the most general and popular division of competitions, which is their type.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Process team data, filter for valid submissions, and categorize teams by member count.\n# Group data by host segment and new member categories, then count occurrences.\nType <- Teams %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = T) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == F) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  filter(is.na(HostSegmentTitle) == F) %>%\n  group_by(HostSegmentTitle, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop')\n\n# Calculate the percentage of non-solo teams specifically within the \"Analytics\" segment.\nRecord_Type <- Type %>%\n  filter(HostSegmentTitle == \"Analytics\") %>%\n  summarise(two_plus = sum(count[Members2 != 1]), all = sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(divide = two_plus / all, percent = paste0(round(divide * 100), \"%\")) %>%\n  pull(percent)\n\n# Format the calculated percentage for display on the plot.\nRecord_Type <- paste0(\"Non-solo teams:\\n\", Record_Type)\n\n# Create a stacked bar plot showing team composition across different competition types.\n# Customize the plot with specific colors, labels, and annotations for clarity.\nggplot(Type, aes(x = HostSegmentTitle, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_x_discrete(limit = c(\"Analytics\", \"Research\", \"Featured\", \"Community\", \"Getting Started\", \"Playground\", \"Recruitment\"))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  annotate(\"text\", x = 1, y = 0.35, label = Record_Type, size = 6, col = \"gray95\")+\n  annotate(geom = \"curve\", xend = 1, y = 0.3, x = 1, yend = 0.18, curvature = 0, arrow = arrow(length = unit(4.5, \"mm\")), colour = \"gray85\", size = 0.6)+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by type of competition\", subtitle = \"in all competitions \\nonly not InClass competitions and teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Type of competition\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:50.907225Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:50.908786Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:38:58.262305Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:38:58.260115Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Kaggle competitions are divided into types defined by the organizers (regardless of whether they are official competitions with medals or communities). The <strong>group of competitions in which teams consisting of 2 or more people make the largest percentage in relation to the rest (at least 10% of all teams) are the Analytics and Research competitions</strong>. Analytics every sixth team is not Superman and it is worth noting the particularly high percentage of Batman & Robin in this category compared to the rest. The <strong>category in which single-person teams dominate the most is recruitment competitions</strong>, because they are usually created to verify the skills of one candidate, so the participation of more than one person is extremely rare.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Next, let's look at the metrics by which submissions are assessed. There are many metrics used in competitions, so we will limit ourselves to only the 10 most popular ones (we measure popularity by the number of submissions to competitions with a specific metric and sort the chart from the most popular ones).</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filters unique teams and processes missing submission IDs.\n# Categorizes teams by member count: 1, 2, or 3+.\nAlgorithm <- Teams %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, .keep_all = T) %>%\n  filter(is.na(PrivateLeaderboardSubmissionId) == F) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  filter(is.na(EvaluationAlgorithmAbbreviation) == F) %>%\n  group_by(EvaluationAlgorithmAbbreviation, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop')\n\n# Calculates percentage of non-solo teams for \"MAP@{K}\" algorithm.\nRecord_Algorithm <- Algorithm %>%\n  filter(EvaluationAlgorithmAbbreviation == \"MAP@{K}\") %>%\n  summarise(two_plus = sum(count[Members2 != 1]), all = sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(divide = two_plus / all, percent = paste0(round(divide * 100), \"%\")) %>%\n  pull(percent)\n\n# Creates a string for the non-solo teams record.\nRecord_Reward <- paste0(\"Non-solo teams: \", Record_Algorithm)\n\n# Generates a bar plot showing team member distribution by evaluation metric.\n# Customizes axes, colors, and adds annotations for specific data.\n# Sets plot title, subtitles, labels, and applies custom themes.\nggplot(Algorithm, aes(x = EvaluationAlgorithmAbbreviation, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.73, alpha = 0.95)+\n  coord_flip()+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_x_discrete(limit = c(\"QuadraticWeightedKappa\", \"FScoreMicro\", \"MAP@{K}\", \"MulticlassLoss\", \"MAE\", \"LogLoss\", \"RMSLE\", \"RMSE\", \"CategorizationAccuracy\", \"AUC\"))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  annotate(\"text\", x = 3, y = 0.28, label = Record_Reward, size = 6, col = \"gray95\")+\n  annotate(geom = \"curve\", xend = 3, y = 0.19, x = 3, yend = 0.126, curvature = 0, arrow = arrow(length = unit(4.5, \"mm\")), colour = \"gray85\", size = 0.6)+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by evaluation metric of competition\", subtitle = \"in all competitions \\nonly not InClass competitions and teams with at least one submission\\nonly top 10 most popular metrics\",\n       x = \"Metrics\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:38:58.264777Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:38:58.266182Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:39:01.953928Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:39:01.952043Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">There is no significant difference in the distributions between the metrics. The largest share of non-solo teams is observed where the metric is MAP@{K}, or Mean Average Precision [17]. A certain tendency can be observed - <strong>in the most obvious and easy-to-understand metrics, especially those related to classifications (such as Accuracy or MulticlassLoss), there is a greater concentration of Supermen, while slightly less obvious metrics (such as MAP or QuadricWightedKappa) have a relatively large share of larger groups</strong>. Could it be that if a competition has a difficult metric, users are eager to support each other in teams to overcome a more difficult challenge?</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Let's move on to what many people like the most about competitions - prizes for the best place/places. For simplicity, the prizes are divided into 5 categories: Cash, Prizes, Kudos/Swag, Knowaldge and Jobs.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Selects relevant columns from 'Teams' and removes duplicate TeamId entries.\n# Creates 'Members2' grouping team sizes into '1', '2', or '3+'.\n# Filters out missing 'Members2' values and groups 'RewardType' into broader categories.\n# Filters for specific 'RewardType_grouped' values, then counts occurrences by group.\nReward <- Teams %>%\n  select(TeamId, RewardType, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\")) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  mutate(RewardType_grouped = case_when(\n    RewardType %in% c(\"USD\", \"EUR\") ~ \"Cash\",\n    RewardType %in% c(\"Kudos\", \"Swag\") ~ \"Kudos/Swag\",\n    T ~ as.character(RewardType))) %>%\n  filter(RewardType_grouped %in% c(\"Cash\", \"Kudos/Swag\", \"Jobs\", \"Knowledge\", \"Prizes\")) %>%\n  group_by(RewardType_grouped, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), .groups = 'drop')\n\n# Filters for 'Cash' rewards, then calculates the percentage of non-solo teams.\n# Formats the result as a percentage string.\nRecord_Reward <- Reward %>%\n  filter(RewardType_grouped == \"Cash\") %>%\n  summarise(two_plus = sum(count[Members2 != 1]), all = sum(count)) %>%\n  mutate(divide = two_plus / all, percent = paste0(round(divide * 100), \"%\")) %>%\n  pull(percent)\n\n# Adds a descriptive prefix to the 'Record_Reward' string.\nRecord_Reward <- paste0(\"Non-solo\\nteams: \", Record_Reward)\n\n# Creates a stacked bar chart showing reward type distribution by team size.\n# Sets custom x-axis order, formats y-axis as percentages, and defines fill colors.\n# Adds a legend title, an annotation with 'Record_Reward', and an arrow pointing to it.\n# Sets chart title, subtitle, axis labels, and caption. Applies custom themes.\nggplot(Reward, aes(x = RewardType_grouped, y = count, fill = Members2)) +\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.7, alpha = 0.95) +\n  scale_x_discrete(limit = c(\"Cash\", \"Prizes\", \"Kudos/Swag\", \"Knowledge\", \"Jobs\")) +\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  annotate(\"text\", x = 1, y = 0.245, label = Record_Reward, size = 6, col = \"gray95\")+\n  annotate(geom = \"curve\", xend = 1, y = 0.2, x = 1, yend = 0.1, curvature = 0, arrow = arrow(length = unit(4.5, \"mm\")), colour = \"gray85\", size = 0.6)+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by reward type\", subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\",\n       x = \"Rewrd type\", fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\", caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:39:01.956394Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:39:01.957973Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:39:06.24908Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:39:06.247205Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Let's look at the distribution of participants depending on the prizes for taking the top places in the competition. <strong>The largest share of teams consisting of two or more people is when the prize is \"cash\"</strong>. Naturally, when money comes into play, increasing the team can bring us closer to this goal, but the value of 9% is not spectacular. A <strong>characteristic category is \"Jobs\", in which only 1-person teams take part </strong>- no wonder, recruitment takes place separately, and the candidate is verified individually, which means that participation in teams from the beginning is usually prohibited.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">And finally, the number of awards, regardless of the category or the number of participants or the number of medals.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Processes team data to categorize the number of prizes and members, then filters out incomplete entries.\nTeams %>%\n  select(TeamId, NumPrizes, Members) %>%\n  distinct(TeamId, `.keep_all` = T) %>%\n  mutate(NumPrizes2 = case_when(NumPrizes < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                                NumPrizes == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                                NumPrizes == 3  ~ \"3\",\n                                NumPrizes == 4  ~ \"4\",\n                                NumPrizes == 5  ~ \"5\",\n                                NumPrizes > 5  ~ \"6+\",\n  )) %>%\n  mutate(Members2 = case_when(Members < 2 ~ \"1\",\n                              Members == 2  ~ \"2\",\n                              Members > 2  ~ \"3+\"\n  )) %>%\n  filter(is.na(Members2) == F) %>%\n  filter(is.na(NumPrizes2) == F) %>%\n  # Groups the data by prize and member categories, then counts occurrences.\n  group_by(NumPrizes2, Members2) %>%\n  summarise(count = n(), , .groups = 'drop') %>%\n  # Creates and customizes a filled bar chart to visualize the distribution of teams by prizes and member count.\nggplot(., aes(x = NumPrizes2, y = count, fill = Members2))+\n  geom_bar(position = \"fill\", stat = \"identity\", width = 0.68)+\n  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#003f5c\", \"#ef5675\", \"#ffa600\"))+\n  guides(fill = guide_legend(title.position = \"top\"))+\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of analyzed groups by number of prizes\",\n       subtitle = \"in all competitions\\nonly teams with at least one submission\", x = \"Number of prizes\",\n       fill = \"Number of Kagglers in team\", y = \"Participation of groups in competitions\",\n       caption = \"© Made by Michau96/Kaggle\")+\n  theme_fivethirtyeight()+\n  theme_michau+\n  theme(legend.title.align = 0.5)","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-07-13T14:39:06.251616Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-07-13T14:39:06.252981Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-07-13T14:39:14.540896Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-07-13T14:39:14.539074Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">More prizes mean more chances to win, so it can be activating. The chart shows a clear relationship - <strong>the more prizes, the greater the number of Batmans with Robins and Avengers in relation to Supermen</strong> (only 3 prizes slightly disturb the more clearly outlined trend). These two groups in competitions with one prize make up less than 5% of participants, while in competitions with more than 5 prizes they make up over 10%.</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: justify\">That's all about the types of contests and prizes... phew, the world of heroes can be complicated, so let's put it all together in a more compact form.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Conclusions","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">Our aim was to investigate how three types of teams evolved over the 15-year history of Kaggle competitions: one-person teams (which we called \"Supermen\"), two-person teams (\"Batman and Robin\"), and three-or-more-person teams (\"Avengers\"). We analyzed this phenomenon based on various factors. Here are the key conclusions from our analysis:</p>\n\n* The Supermen (people participating in competitions on their own) are definitely the dominant group in the world of data superheroes\n* It is difficult to point out a clear reason for such dominance, the papers suggests it may be the effect of \"social loafing\", a smaller number of distractions and the need for autonomy and greater control over the project\n* Supermen dominance does not occur in another AI-related activity - paper writing, among which Superman is the rarest group and Avengers the most popular\n* Supermen dominance is visible in all years since the beginning, the differences between years are small\n* It is predicted that in the coming years, Supermen dominance may continue to deepen at the expense of other groups at a slow pace\n* \"Santander Consumer Transaction Prediction\" was the most popular competition among single and double groups, but \"Home Credit - Credit Risk Model Stability\" gathered the largest number of groups with 3+ members\n* The number of submissions is higher the larger the team is\n* Among the medals, especially gold ones, the share of Batman & Robin and Avengers is definitely (!) higher than in the entire population\n* The share of medals (both gold and non-gold) won by larger teams increased steadily until 2018, after which there was a stabilization\n* Stabilization in the distribution of medals between groups is expected in the coming years, but a sharp increase in the percentage of gold medals won by one-man armies is likely\n* \"Analytics\" competitions attracted the most teams of 2+ people, while recruitment competitions are popular only among Supermen\n* Classification model competitions with simple metrics are home to Supermen, while less obvious metrics have an above-average share of larger teams\n* Cash and a large number of prizes encourage participants to start together, while recruitment and small prizes are particularly favored by 1-person teams","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">What is the main conclusion for people who work on Kaggle on a daily basis? <strong>Don't be fooled into thinking that team building is a sideshow on Kaggle. It's true that teams are rare (even rarer than you might think), but they win prizes and medals disproportionately to their population, so is it worth it to start a team for the next competition and compete with others?</strong> You can look for team partners on competition forums, the official Discord or through less official channels such as co-workers or college friends.</p>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p style=\"text-align: justify\">And remember, even though we are different, we make up a great community of data superheroes. We don't fight against anyone, but like superheroes we try to solve the problems that are chaos in the data from which we want to \"save\" valuable information. <strong>It doesn't matter whether you start as Superman, Batman & Robin or the Avengers - the most important thing is fair competition, expanding your knowledge and having fun!</strong> 😎</p>\n\n![](https://media.giphy.com/media/3avUsGhmckIYE/giphy.gif)\n\nSpecial thanks to all commentators for important feedback on the project, especially [Tensor Girl](https://www.kaggle.com/usharengaraju)!\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 12px;font-style: italic\">Some code comments and single lines of code were created using Generative Artificial Intelligence (Gemini Flash 2.5). All descriptions and most of the code were created by [myself](https://www.kaggle.com/michau96).</span>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**References**\n1. https://www.kaggle.com/docs\n2. https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/index.html\n3. https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/\n4. https://www.kaggle.com/code/michau96/15-factors-for-data-science-in-your-country\n5. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kaggle/meta-kaggle\n6. [Karau, Steven & Williams, Kipling. (1993). Social Loafing: A Meta-Analytic Review and Theoretical Integration. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology.](http://www.communicationcache.com/uploads/1/0/8/8/10887248/social_loafing-_a_meta-analytic_review_and_theoretical_integration.pdf)\n7. [Brumby, Duncan & Janssen, Christian & Mark, Gloria. (2019). How Do Interruptions Affect Productivity?](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/332917086_How_Do_Interruptions_Affect_Productivity)\n8. [Ma, Yimeng & Huang, Yu & Leach, Kevin. (2024). Breaking the Flow: A Study of Interruptions During Software Engineering Activities.](https://kjl.name/papers/icse24.pdf)\n9. [Richard M. Ryan and Edward L. Deci. (2000). Self-Determination Theory and the Facilitation of Intrinsic Motivation, Social Development, and Well-Being.](https://selfdeterminationtheory.org/SDT/documents/2000_RyanDeci_SDT.pdf)\n10. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/yasirabdaali/arxivorg-ai-research-papers-dataset\n11. https://arxiv.org/\n12. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_regression\n13. https://www.kaggle.com/c/santander-customer-transaction-prediction/overview\n14. https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/m5-forecasting-accuracy\n15. https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/home-credit-default-risk\n16. https://www.widsworldwide.org/\n17. https://sdsawtelle.github.io/blog/output/mean-average-precision-MAP-for-recommender-systems.html\n\n\n**Inspiration for creating data storytelling**\n- [Knaflic, Cole Nussbaumer. (2015). Storytelling with Data: A Data Visualization Guide for Business Professionals.](https://www.amazon.pl/Storytelling-Data--Visualization-Business-Professionals/dp/1119002257)\n- [Biecek, Przemysław. (2014). Odkrywać! Ujawniać! Objaśniać! Zbiór esejów o sztuce prezentowania danych.](http://biecek.pl/Eseje/)","metadata":{}}]}